## Order

Do you need a PSKE quickly? Then we will guide you through the ordering process here:

### Customer portal

Start the ordering process in our customer portal.

### Selection Managed Kubernetes

Navigate to Cloud Services > Managed Kubernetes.

![](data:image/png;base64,)


Order ### Managed Kubernetes

Select 'Order PSKE now'.

![](data:image/png;base64,
)

Select your infrastructure.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Select billing profile

Are you a new plusserver customer and do not yet receive an invoice? Then select New billing profile.

Are you already a customer? Then you can choose from existing billing profiles and receive the new PSKE on an existing invoice, so search for your billing profile under Existing billing profile.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Select e-mail for deployment information

Enter the e-mail address to which all relevant information on the provision of the PSKE should be sent, such as status updates or passwords.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Select onboarding workshop

If you would like to take advantage of our onboarding workshop on PSKE by one of our employees, please check the appropriate box.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Advice on further supplementary services

If you would like to find out more about other supplementary services, please also select our offer for a consultation on this topic.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Security Operations Center

This service will be available for you soon.


### Triggering the order

Please check your entered data via the summary. Please read the terms and conditions and agreements and confirm them. Only then can you complete the order by clicking on Order now for a fee.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Track order status

You will be forwarded to the order status immediately after placing your order. You can view the status of current orders here at any time.

- NEW: Status directly after the order
- PROCESSING: Status as soon as automatic provision has started
- FAILED: Unfortunately something has gone wrong, please open a ticket here in the portal so that we can help you as quickly as possible.
- DONE: Congratulations, your PSKE is available

### View access data

Immediately after placing your order, you can jump directly from the order to the contract. You will find the access data there. You can also find the access data at any time via the contracts.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

#### Overview

You should now see this overview (clusters already exist in this demo).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Cluster creation

#### Infrastructure Provider

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. With pluscloud open, you use a digitally sovereign, BSI-C5-tested cloud based on OpenStack.
2. alternatively, we also offer the option of deploying your clusters on the AWS infrastructure.

### Cluster details

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. the cluster name can be freely selected - the characters are only restricted by lowercase [a-z] or digits [0-9] (no special characters).
2. the Kubernetes version can be freely selected (we recommend using the latest version, as this supports all common Kubernetes features).
Versions that are EOL are marked accordingly.
3. select the purpose of the cluster here. The following default settings are made (which can of course be adjusted):
   1. for "evaluation", the cluster shuts down at the end of the working day (17:00), but does not start up again.
   2. for "development", it shuts down automatically (at 5 p.m.) and starts up again (at 8 a.m.).
   3. with "testing", no monitoring and logging is deployed from our side for the cluster.
   4. no hibernation schedule is stored for "production", it runs 24/7.

### Infrastructure Details

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. under "Cloud Profile" you specify in which of our data centers your cluster should run. 
2. the secret for the pluscloud open has already been stored by us and cannot be deleted or changed by you.
3. depending on the selected cloud profile, the region is automatically stored accordingly (prod1 => DE-WEST (Cologne), prod2 => DE-NORTH (Hamburg) and prod3 => DE-NORTH (Hamburg). 
This refers to the location of the data centers in Cologne and Hamburg (we have two data centers here).
4. we recommend using the preselection "Cilium" as the "Networking Type".

### Worker

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. the group name can be chosen freely, the characters are only restricted by lowercase [a-z] or digits [0-9] (only the "-" character is allowed as a special character).
2) We only support the "amd64" architecture.
3. different flavors can be selected here under "Machine Type" (e.g. SCS-16V:64:100 - Sovereign Cloud Stack (SCS)), which differ in the combination of CPU cores and RAM.
4) Flatcar or Ubuntu is currently available as the "Machine Image" for the workers.
5. containerd or docker can be selected as "Container Runtime". We recommend using the preselection containerd, as docker support no longer exists in more recent Kubernetes versions. 
6. the required "Volume Size" for the worker can be configured here, a later downsizing of the volume is possible via the dashboard in the self-service.
The downsizing is performed as a rolling upgrade, which means that the old worker is replaced by a new worker with the new sizing.
7. autoscaling can be used to define the max and min number and the number of steps in which further workers are started. The autoscaler works on the basis of the requested resources of the workers, a detailed explanation can be found here https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/ 
8 AZ = Availability Zones, spanning several fire sections.

### Maintenance

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. a maintenance window for auto updates (operating system and Kubernetes patch version) can be configured here. We recommend defining a maintenance window and checking the box under "Auto Updates".
2. the updates for the operating system of the workers are carried out via rolling update, i.e. a worker is taken out and a new worker with updates carried out is taken in.
3. to ensure that the Kubernetes cluster always supports all features, continuous patching of the Kubernetes version is necessary.

### Hibernation

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. the days on which you want to start up or shut down your cluster in order to save resources and therefore costs.
2. the time at which the cluster is to be woken up can be specified here.
3. the time at which the cluster is to be shut down is specified here.

## Kubeconfig
In order to be able to interact with a cluster, a Kubeconfig must be available.

### Download der Kubeconfig

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. download the Kubeconfig via the key symbol in the bar of the respective cluster.
2. in the new window, simply click on the download symbol.

### Using the Kubeconfig

The downloaded Kubeconfig should ideally be stored in the ".kube" folder in the home directory of the respective user.

```mv {KUBECONFIG-NAME}.yaml ~/.kube/```

This can then be exported.

```export KUBECONFIG=~/.kube/{KUBECONFIG-NAME}.yaml```
